LAUNCH-SAVING REALIZED vs THEORETICAL
  per-launch overhead (measured, 18 noop back-to-back best-of-300): 1.81 us.
  grid.sync unit cost (measured, isolated): 0.85 us.
  gross launch saving  : (18-2) x 1.81 = 28.9 us/layer.
  grid.sync paid       : 10 syncs x 0.85 = 8.5 us/layer.
  net theoretical win  : 28.9 - 8.5 = ~20.4 us/layer.
  realized @ L=1024    : 74.0 - 65.8 = ~8.2 us/layer (~40% of net theoretical;
                         ~28% of gross launch saving).
  WHAT SWAMPED IT: the fused kernel BODY is slightly slower than the sum of
  eager's optimized per-op kernel bodies -- (a) flash-merge reads KW partials
  serially per head; (b) 10 grid.sync barriers serialize phases, defeating the
  cross-kernel latency-hiding the GPU does between independent eager launches;
  (c) cooperative-launch occupancy/grid-size is a single global config (GRID=120
  optimal), can't be retuned per phase like eager's 18 independent grids.

CROSSOVER : L ~ 1536. For L <= 1024 (launch-bound) fusion wins +3 to +11%;
  for L >= 1536 (attention compute/memory-bound) eager's per-phase-tuned
  key-parallel attention scales better and fusion loses.

